Plotting Population Data

Emilio Luz-Ricca

  • 1 Bringing in Raster Data
  • 2 Aggregating Population Data to the Region-Level
  • 3 Aggregating Population Data to the Tinkhundla-Level

1 Bringing in Raster Data

The first step of this exercise was to acquire raster data for population. I again used Swaziland, although I plan to focus in on just the Manzini region in the future (mostly because it has a relatively small population of about 366786).

The first step here was to read in the raster data using raster::raster(). Once brought in, I made a simple plot using base R.

This all looks as expected. We can even begin to see some more densely populated areas (the city Manzini and the capital Mbabane).

2 Aggregating Population Data to the Region-Level

Next, I performed the parallel processing techniques as laid out in the exercise to aggregate the raster population data to the first level of administrative boundaries (regions). Then, combining this data with the sf geometry data, I used ggplot to plot the results.

3 Aggregating Population Data to the Tinkhundla-Level

Finally, I aggregated to the tinkhundla level and plotted the results once again. Its worth noting that the fill aesthetic is mapping to the natural logarithm of population.

We can zoom in to just our region of interest, Manzini, as well.
